SIMPLE: falter
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Falter
<hw>Fal"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To thrash in the
chaff; also, to cleanse or sift, as barley.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Falter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Falter
<hw>Fal"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Faltered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Faltering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>falteren</ets>,
<ets>faltren</ets>, prob. from <ets>fault</ets>. See <er>Fault</er>,
<pos>v. & n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To hesitate; to speak
brokenly or weakly; to stammer; <as>as, his tongue
<ex>falters</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With <qex>faltering</qex> speech and visage incomposed.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To tremble; to totter; to be unsteady.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧He found his legs <xex>falter</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Wiseman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hesitate in purpose or action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ere her native king⟦br⟧
Shall <qex>falter</qex> under foul rebellion's arms.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To fail in distinctness or regularity of exercise;
-- said of the mind or of thought.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here indeed the power of disinct conception of space and distance
<qex>falters</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Falter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Falter
<hw>Fal"ter</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter with hesitation, or in
a broken, trembling, or weak manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And here he <qex>faltered</qex> forth his last farewell.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mde me most happy, <qex>faltering</qex> ⟦ldquo⟧I am
thine.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 541 --></p>

<p><ent>Falter</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Falter
<hw>Fal"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Falter</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety> <def>Hesitation; trembling; feebleness; an
uncertain or broken sound; <as>as, a slight <ex>falter</ex> in her
voice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>falter</qex> of an idle shepherd's pipe.</q>
<rj><qau>Lowell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Faltering</ent>⟦br⟧
